  "response_text": "The simulation demonstrates stable average risk attitudes across all agent types throughout the 100-step timeline. Initial risk values cluster tightly around baseline levels: \u2019E-RO\u2019 maintains a neutral position near 0.0; \u2019E-LBD\u2019 and \u2019E-RO-SL1\u2019 display moderate risk aversion at 0.15 and 0.10 respectively; while specialized subgroups (\u2019brown\u2019, \u2019orange\u2019, \u2019green\u2019) exhibit higher avoidance tendencies (0.12-0.18). Notably, no adaptive shifts occur despite climatic variability (mean rainfall 200, std 100) or social learning parameters (knowledge radius=1). This reflects the model\u2019s design where learning mechanisms (E-LBD, E-RO-SL1) operate independently of behavioral type distinctions in homogeneous configurations. The fixed resting threshold (0.1) and satisficing trials (21) likely constrain decision-making variability, preserving initial risk profiles. Climate-driven biomass fluctuations might indirectly influence risk perceptions, but the absence of strategy switching (SL2-strategy-switch?=False) and intrinsic preference weighting (0.0) prevents measurable behavioral adaptation. These patterns underscore the E-RO type\u2019s resilience in homogeneous settings, with risk attitudes acting as stable decision filters rather than dynamic variables."  
